{"/service/ndnp/nvln/batch_nvln_jackpot_ver01/data/sn86091313/00332891315/1908041701/0064.xml":{"full_text":"LO _ TRIBUNE\nVOL. XI. NO. 14. LOVELOCK. HUMBOLDT COUNTY. NEVADA. FRIDAY. APRIL 17. 1908. FIVE CENTS PER COPY\nANOTHER DEAL\nMADE AT JESSUP\nSan Francisco Capitalists Buy\nBandy Claim.\nPrice Said to Be $3500 and a large\nStock Consideration\u2014Big Force\nof Miners Will Thoroughly Devel\nop the Property.\nThe fourth big deal for the Jessup\ndistrict was consummated tho fore\npart of this week when Adolph Kunze\nand San Francisco associates secured\nan option on the Dandy claim located\nabout two miles west of the town of\nJessup. The option runs for a period\nof 25 days and the price is $3500\nwith a stock consideration. The\nDandy claim belongs to William Opper\nman; Eomie Cunningham, J. J. Wilson,\nDr. DeGruyter and T. Cruse, all well\nknown Lovelockers.\nMr. Opperman, who has been in\nthe district for the past three weeks\nlooking after the development of bis\nproperty, was in Lovelock the fore\npart of this week closing tne deal for\nbis crowd, lie stated that very little\nwork had been done on the Dandy\nclaim as yet, but that in running\ntrenches on the surface a 20 foot\nledge had been cut, about three feet\nof the main ledge lying next to the\nhanging wall carries values ranging\nall the way from $60 to $100 in gold\nto the ton and the character of the\nrock is very similar to that found in\nthe Hopkins property.\nMr. Kunze, who has just secured\nthe option on the Dandy, has started\nseveral miners to work and it is his\nintentions to thoroughly prospect\nthe ground. Besides running\ntrenches through the big ledge cut\nting through the claim, he will sink a\nnumber of prospect holes.\nMessrs. Opperman and associates\nhave several claims adjoining the\nDandy for which an offer has already\nbeen made but the owners have de\ncided to hold them and are now plan\nning to commence active develop\nment. On the Dandy No 1. a very\nstrong ledge outcrops and when a\nsuitable spot is located a shaft will\nbe sunk.\nMr. Opperman is very enthusiastic\nover the future outlook for the new\ndistrict and says that substantial\nstrikes are a daily occurrence. The\ntown is rapidly assuming metropoli\ntan airs and a number of frame store\nbuildings and residences are being\nbuilt.\nAttempt to Crack Safe\nBurglars entered the store of the\nUtah-Nevada Supply company at\nHumboldt House Sunday night, but.\nwere frightened away before any\nthing of value was stolen. The knob\nand combination of the safe were\nbroken with a sledge hammer, but for\nsome reason the burglars did not\nmanage to get the door of the strong\nbox open and consequently no money\nwas taken. When the store was\nopened in the morning by the clerk\nthere was every evidence that the\nplace had been entered by burglars\nduring the night and that they were\nevidently frightened away by some\none approaching the building while\nthey were at work.\nHas Faith In Jessup\nL. L. Hogerton, who with asso\nciates, owns several promising claims\nin the JesBup district, was in town\nthis Week on a short business trip.\nMr. Hogerton is very enthusiastic\nover the showings being made over\nthe district and has no hesitancy in\npredicting a great future for the\nnew camp.\n'\u2018A Case of Suspension\u201d\nA home talent drama entitled, \u201cA\nCase of Suspension\" will be given at,\nthe Big Meadow school house Friday\nevening, April 24. A fancy booth\nwill be conducted and refreshments\nserved. Admission 25 cents.\nGrowing Steadily\nGeorge Taylor, the Jessup mining\nman, was in Lovelock several days\nthis week on a combined business\nand pleasure trip. Mr. Taylor says\nthe town of Jessup is growing very\nrapidly and that more than 500 peo\nple have taken up a permanent resi\ndence there.\nHas Close Call\nJoe White, a tramp, was brought\nto Lovelock from Humboldt House\nthe first of this week suffering from\na compound fracture of the left leg,\na severe scalp wound and many bruises\n'about the body. White was drunk and\nvery little could be learned about\nhim but the supposition is that ha\nfell from a train and received the\ninjuries. Drs. Pinniger and West\ndressed the wounds and the unfortu\nnate man was sent to the county\nhospital at Winnemucca.\nA Clean Show\nThe flood gates of laughter will be\nthrown wide open at the School House\nhall next Saturday and Sunday even\ning when the Pavilla Comedy company\nwill start a riotof sizzling merriment.\nAnd the beauty of it all is that\neverything they do is clean and moral\nbut at the same time excruciatingly\nfunny. The Pavilla company visited\nLovelock several years ago at which\ntime they won the hearts of the\ntheatre going people.\nWill Locate Here\nRichard Harris, a prominent min\ning man from Elkton, Colo, arrived\nin Lovelock last week and will locate\nhere permanently. Mr. Harris who\nis a warm personal friend of William\nHauston, the Lovelock contractor, is\nvery favorably impressed with this\nsection of the country and he is loud\nin his predictions that the immediate\nsurrounding mining sections will\nprove a great boon to this part of\nthe state.\n\nSeeking Health at Coast\nGebrge H. Wood, manager for the\nMcIntosh Department store, accom\npained his wife to San Francisco last\nMonday night. Mrs. Wood has been\na sufferer from rheumatism for sev\neral weeks and she will visit Byron\nSprings and other health resorts in\nthe hopes of regaining her health.\nMr. Wood expects to return to Love\nlock in about a week or ten days.\nCommences Active Work\nDave Baker and William Daily\nleft Wednesday morning for Trinity\nPeak district where they will remain\nfor several days. Both Messrs. Baker\nand Daily were successful in securing\na number of promising claims in that\ndistrict recently and it is there in\ntentions to commence active develop\nment work.\nInspects Interests\nMiss 0. M. Crockett, chief clerk of\nthe money order department of the\nGoldfield postoffice, was in Lovelock\nthe early part of this week, after\nspending several days in the Seven\nTroughs district inspecting her min\ning interests. Miss Crockett, who\nis well posted in the mining business,\nis very enthusiastic over the future\noutlook of the Seven Troughs dis\ntrict.\nMonster Mining Vein\nGut on Lipps Estate\n\u201cOperations on the Comet and\nMeter claims,\u201d said Joe Lipps, the\nSeven Troughs mining man, \u201cis pro\ngressing very satisfactorily. The\nproperty is being worked both by\nleasers and on company account and\nthe developments during the past\nfew weeks have been far beyond our\nexpectations.\u201d\nMr. Lipps was in Lovelock the\nearly days of the week looking after\nimportant business matters and in a\nshort talk with a Tribune representa\ntive he stated that his company was\nlosing no time in opening np its\npossessions. The shaft has been\nsunk to a depth of 75 feet and from\nthis point a 90-foot crosscut has\nbeen run. In running the crosscut\nan 18-foot ledge of high grade mill\ning ore was cut. The big ledge has\nbeen prospected and developed by\ndrif ts and crosscuts and careful\nsampling shows the values running\nall the way from $10 to $26. As\nsoon as arrangements can be made\nthe ore will be taken out and treated\nat one of the new mills that are now\nbeing erected in the district.\nMcQuaid and McDaniel, operating\na lease on the Lipps prop\nerty, have ordered a new hoisting\nplant and its arrival is looked for\nsoon. The shaft on the lease is 53\nfeet deep and when the machinery is\nin place the shaft will be continued\nto the 100-foot mark. Wolcott and\nMorrow, also operating a lease on\nthe Lipps estate, have sunk a shaft\nto a depth of 65 feet.\nMontana Business Man\nWill Locate In Nevada\nE. A. Cherry, a former resident of\nButte, Mont., who has been visiting\nwith his parents in Delta, Colo., for\nthe past four months arrived in Love\nlock last Saturday, and will remain\nhere some time as the guest of his\nbrother, H. W. Cherry of the Tribune.\nMr. Cherry, who has been in the\nelectrical business in the Montana me-1\ntropolis for a number of years, has de- j\ncided to forsake his former business\nand get into the \u201cmining game\u201dand has\nchosen Nevada as the spot in which\nto seek his fortune. He will visit\nthe Jessup, Seven Troughs and other\ndistricts surrounding Lovelock.\n\u201cNevada,\u201d said Mr. Cherry, \u201cis at\ntracting a great deal of attention\namong the capitalists and mining\nmen of Butte and a number have\nsignified their intentions of visiting\nthe statejwitha view to making invest\nments. It is true the country is just\nemerging from a very bad financial\npanic, but from the sharp advances\nin the industrial stocks and the gen\neral restoration of confidence in all\nbranches of business, it is my firm be\nlief that the mining industry in Ne\nvada will receive more attention dur\ning the present year than ever before\nin the history of the state.\u201d\nSan Francisco Lawyer\nPraises Jessup District\nHoward K. James, formerly a law\nyer in San Francisco and now asso\nciated with Stuart Armour of San\nFrancisco in tile ownership of copper\nproperties near Jessup, arrived in the\ncity last evening on a business trip\nand states that he believes Jessup is\none of the best of the new mining\ncamps of the state, says the Gazette.\n\u201cThe people at Jessup are after\nmines and are not trying to fool the\npeople,\u201d said Mr. James. \u201cThey\nknow that the Jessup district con\ntains some good ledges and they are\ndeveloping them. The town has\nnever been boomed but it is building\nrapidly and in a short time there will\nbe a rush into that district, equal to\nthe great rush into Rawhide. When\nthe rush is started there will already\nbe some paying mines in the camp.\u201d\nWill Erect New Residence\nJust as soon as arrangements can\nbe made Dr. McDonald will let con\ntracts for his new residence on the\nlot just east of Dr. Martin\u2019s horn e.\nThe new building to be erected by\nDr. McDonald will be 30x50 one story\nframe. It will be a double affair\nand a portion of it will be rented.\nCOMMERCIAL LEAGUE\nMEMBERS BANQUETED\nCiOzens of Lovelock Tender Visitors Warm Re\nception and Large Crowd Enjoys Sumptu\nous Repast at Northern Cafe- Visitors Loud\nIn The r Praise of Entertainment.\nNot for many years has there been\na meeting in Lovelock that meant so\nmuch for the progress of Humboldt\ncounty as the banquent given by the\nLovelock Commercial club to the\ntwenty-five visitors from the Nevada\nCommercial League at the Northern\nCafe last Wednesday night. The\nvisitors and local citizens present\nwere in their most cheerful mood\nand the banquet was conducted\nthroughout in a veritable flood-tide\nof good cheer.\nL. G. Campbell of Lovelock acted\nas toastmaster. In welcoming the\nguests he spoke briefly of the re\nsources of of the town of Lovelock\nand vicinity, stating the number of\ncarloads of livestock shipped from\nthis station annually and estimating\nthe value of all property both real\nand personal in and about Lovelock\nat twelve million dollars.\nMany of the guests responded\nwhen called upon, with speeches\nhighly amusing and instructive. A\nnumber of our citizens also responded\nwith good stories and information\nt I..\nconcerning Humboldt county. An\noriginal poem by Mr. McPherson of\nLovelock, was a feature that wa3\nheartily received and loudly ap\nplauded by all present.\nIn short the banquet was in every\nway a success and many congratula\ntions were offered to the committee\nhaving its arrangement in charge.\nThe guests left in their special\ncar for Golconda, at which point they\nleave the railroad and visit Gold\nCircle, the new camp in Elko county.\nOn their return trip they will speud\na day at Jessup.\nIn speaking of their reception in\nthe towns of the Seven Troughs dis\ntrict, the members of the league in\none accord paid the highest tribute\nto the citizens of that district for\nthe royal entertainment accorded\nthem. They were shown about the\nmines of the district and many were\nthe expressions that thoSevenTroughs\ndistrict \u201cwas the greatest on earth.\u201d\nA banquet had been prepared for the\nvisitors and fully 50 people sat down\nto enjoy the spread by Mine Host\nMorrison of the Mazuma hotel.\nCounties Contribute\nSeveral counties have already re\nsponded to the call of thfr Nevada\nPublicity Bureau to furnish funds for\nthe purpose of insuring a suitable dis\nplay of Nevada ores at the Inter\nnational Mining Exhibition, which\nopens in New York City in May.\nFunds amounting to nearly $3,000\nhave been subscribed and proffers of\nassistance have been received from\nmany mining men throughout the\nstate. Should all the counties of the\nstate contribute the amount legalized\nby the Legislature for this purpose\nthe fund will amount to $5,000.\n\nOpen Opera House\nAll arrangements have been per\nfected for the dance to be given next\nSaturday evening and which will mark\nthe informal opening of the Nixon\nopera house, says the Star. Mrs. Geo.\nS. Nixon will be the guest of honor\nof the occasion and that there will\nbe a large attendance goes without\nsaying, as this will afford the first\nopportunity for the people of Winne\nmucca to inspect the magnificent\nnew opera house and for the devotees\nof Terpsichore to enjoy themselves\nby the use of the finest dancing floor\nin the state.\nBert Olson, the Seven Troughs\nlawyer, was a passenger to Salt Lake\nCity yesterday.\nBusiness Outlook Good\nJ. A. McIntosh, proprietor of Mc\nIntosh\u2019s Department store, came from\nBerkeley the first of this week and\nwill remain here looking after his\nbusiness during the absence of Man\nager Woods. Mr. McIntosh, who is\none of the pioneers of Lovelock, is\nmore than pleased with the rapid\ngrowth the town is making and pre\ndicts that it will soon rank as one of\nthe best business centers in the state.\nFirst Paper for Jessup\nThe first paper to enter the new\ntown of Jessup in the Jessup district\nwas issued from the press of the Ne\nvada Forum at Sparks on Monday of\nthis week. The new publication will\nbe known as the Jessup News and\nwill be edited^ by Mr. Purcell. The\nfirst issue is brim full of good news\nof the mines of the camp. Success\nto the News.\nRemove Central Office\nThe Northern Nevada Telephone\nTelegraph company is preparing to\nremove its central office to the Mc\nIntosh Department store. A room\nhas been partitioned off from the dry\ngoods department and when finished\nwill be larger and more convenient\nthan the old office. It is expected\nthat everything will be in readiness\nto move by the first of the coming\nweek.\nWill Resume Operations\nC. W. Gilman, general manager for\nthe Nevada-California Mining com\npany, arrived from Ijob Angeles last\nTuesday and will remain here in\ndefinitely. Mr. Gilman announces\nthat active operations will be re\nsumed at _once|on the Nevada-Cali\nfornia property in the Trinity range\nPlans have been made to carry out\nthe work on a much larger scale than\never befbre and the management ex\npects some sensational development\nbefore work has progressed very far.\nAgency at Huxley.\nOwing to the increased traffic to\nJessup the Southern Pacific will in\nthe near future establish an agency\nat Huxley. At the present time all\nthe Huxley business is transacted\nthrough the Sparks office and the ar\nrangement necessitates considerable\ndelay and inconvenience. Agent Fod\nrin says that the Huxtey business has\ngrown to very large proportions and\n(hat an agency for the Jessup station\nis greatly needed.\u2014Forum.\nConcert and Dance\nThe members of the Big Meadows\nband are planning an entertainment\nwhich will be given at the Marker\nschool house next Monday evening\nBesides giving a concert, dancing\nwill be indulged in and a good time\nia guaranteed to all. An admission\nfee of 50 cents will be charged and\nthe proceeds will be used for the\npurch ase of music and instruments.\nStork Visits Two Homes\nTha stork visited two Lovelock\nhomes last Sunday morning and left\ntwo \u201cprize winners\u201d to gladden the\nhearts of the parents. At the home\nof Mr. and Mrs. Charles Romwall at\nPitts ranch a 9-pound boy was born,\nwhile a 9-pound girl was born to Mr\nand Mrs. John Faunt. All concerned\nare reported to be doing nicely.\n\nLeaves For Coast\nW. S. Ulmer, of the Stauts-Ulmer\ncompany, the Lovelock mining brok\nerage firm, left last Tuesday evening\nfor California points. Mr. Ulmer\nwill visit San Francisco, San Jose,\nSanta Barbara and Los Angeles and\nduring his absence he will transact\nimportant mining business. He ex\npects to be gone about a month.\nDance At Jessup\nA. Benedetti, the Lovelock mer\nchant, returned from Jessup the first\nof this week where he had been for a\nfew days looking after his interests.\nMr. Benedetti stated that the second\nsuccessful dance was given in the\nnew camp last week, which was at\ntended and enjoyed by a large crowd.\n\nBack from Carson\nFrank Crumpacker, the mining\nman and senior member of the firm\nof Crumpacker Sims, real estate\nand mining brokers has returned from\nan extended visit to Carson City.\nLovelock Wins First\nGame of the Season\nThe first game of baseball to be\nplayed in Lovelock was pulled off at\nthe baseball park last Sunday be\ntween the second teams of YVinne\nmucca and Lovelock. The game was\nwon by the home toam, the score be\ning 17 to 8. Notwitstanding the\nnumber of hits by both sides, some\nremarkably scientific plays were\nmade and the 200 spectators enjoyed\nthe sport to the fullest extent.\nThe home team played very strong\nball and with the material it has it is\na safe wager that before the season\nis over the second team of Lovelock\nwill rank as one of the best in the\nstate. The following was the lineup\nat last Sunday's game:\nLovelock\u2014L. Young, pitcher; B.\nLadd, catcher; W. Bachrodt, first\nbase; C. Pollock, second base; D.\nEngasser, third base; J. Welch, short\nstop; C. Young, right field: T. C\nYoung, center field; K. Hill, left field.\nWinnemucca\u2014F. Case, pitcher; M.\nYoung, catcher; R. Case, first base;\nKenhel, second base; Bounifield, third\nbase; W. Case, Short stop; Duhl,\nright field, Schmidt, center field;\nBalder, left field. Umpire, J. Witt;\nscore keeper, F. A. Preston.\nIncorporate Jessup Property\nArticles of incorporation of the\nJessup Consolidated Mining company\nwere filed with the county clerk of\nWashoe county last Tuesday. The\ncapitalization of the organization is\nplaced at $1,000,000. The incor\nporators are K. 0. Johnson, G. E.\nBigelow, J. M. Benton and A. E. Baker.\nHIGH ASSAYS\nFROM LEASE\nI\nStrike on English-George\nProperty Improves.\nFive Inch Streak Disclosed Near Sur\nface Yields Assay Returns Running\nInto the Thousands-Owners Will\nDevelop on a Very Large Scale.\nThe strike on the English George\nlease on the Badger claim of the\nFine Gold group in the Seven Troughs\ndistrict, continues to be the center\nof attraction among mining men at\nthat camp, and if the conditions con\ntinue to improve as they have during\nthe past week, it will only be a mat\nter of a very short time until an\nother regular producer will be added\nto the already large list. A force\nof miners is at work on the new find\nand a number of sacks of very rich\nore has been taken out.\nFred A. Preston, the Lovelock\nmerchant, who is associated with\nMessrs. English and George in the\nlease returned the first of this week\nfrom Mazuma where he has been\nmaking an inspection of the prop\nerty. He stated the pav streak was\nfully five inches in wjdth and speci\nmens which he brought in showed\nthe yellow metal in large quantities.\nThe rock from the new strike has\nbeen assayed and the values run all\nthe wav from $3700 to $30,000. The\nextent of the main ledge has not\nbeen determined sb vet, but at pres\nent it shows a width of fully five\nfeet and the general average values\nshow a good shipping grade.\nMr. Preston stated that seven men\nwere at work at present and that\nplans had been made to develop\nthe lease on a very large scale, A\nbhaft will be sunk on the new find\nand when the proper depth is at\ntained, crosscutting will be com\nmenced. A tunnel is also being\ndriven on a very strong ledge which\nyields good values. The tunnel will\nbe continued to a point below where\nthe rich find was made on the sur\nface and when the proper distance\nhas been reached a crosscut will be\nrun in the hopes of locating the high\ngrade streak which has just been\nopened on the surface.\nThe owners are confident they\nhave a bonanza and are exerting\nevery power to open up their prop\nerty in the shortest time possible.\nl\nThe Pavilla Company\nThe I\u2019avilla company opened its\ntwo nights\u2019 engagement last evening\nto a good audience that was enter\ntained and made to laugh at or ad\nmire the action every moment be\ntween the first raising of the curtain\nto its final drop. It is a good, clean\nshow. One that can be enjoyed by\none\u2019s wife, sister, mother, and it is\na first-class show, worth several times\nthe price of admission. This evening\na complete change of bill. Attend\nand you will be pleased.\u2014Boise\nStatesman.\n--i\nFailed to Show Up.\nThe bank commissioners of Neveda\nhad called a meeting for the board of\ndirectors of the State Bank and Trust\ncompany, to be held in Carson Wed\nnesday, for the purpose of forming a\nplan for the opening of the banks, but\nthe bank commissioners failed to show\nup. Nearly all of the directors of the\nbank were present.\nW. B. Sullivan Dead.\nWord was received in Lovelock the\nfore part of this week that W. B.\nSullivan, formerly of Farrell, but\nmore recently of Rawhide, had passed\naway at tt e latter camp. I\u2019neumonia\nwas the direct cause of Mr. Sullivan\u2019s\ndeath and from reports it is said he\nwas sick only a few hours.\nOpens Plumbing Shop\nJoseph Elton has erected a build\ning on the lot next to May's Ilakery\nand will open a tinning and plumbing\nshop the first of the week. The new\nconcern will be known as the Love\nlock Sheet Metal Works.\n\nNew Barber Shop\nC. E. Peterson has opened a bar\nber shop in the Ix>velock saloon. Mr.\nPeterson, besides being a tonsorial\nartist, is a jeweler and will do watch\nrepairing in connection with bis bar\nber business.","height":"24272","width":"16636"}}
